SummaryOfEvents:
After the fishing labour, the vessel went to be moored (for 2 days during the weekend) at Matosinhos and stored its fishing nets with mackerel waste, inside the fish closed deck (only with one sidelight/porthole supposedly semi-opened). 

Due to the fact that the decomposition of this fish fat usually creates a volatile and extremely flammable gas called trimethylamine (IUPAC name: N,N-dimethylmethanamine), supposedly overcame its threshold concentration of inflammability in the air, being necessary only a spark to ignite it. Explosion lower limit :  2,0  Vol.-% (49 g/m3) Explosion upper limit: 11,6  Vol.- %   (285  g/m3) 

When the victim, on course of his duties on board the fishing vessel, arrived to the kitchen which is right next to the fish closed deck (connected by an opened door at the time), he felt an intense smell of rotten fish and/or ammonia-like, but anyway he switched a lighter. By doing this, caused the ignition and a violent spreading of the fire (explosion) also to the places nearby that had oxygen to burn (dining/rest room and sleeping room). This caused a violent consumption of oxygen and therefore, burned the victim, fixtures (luminaries), a television set and caused the bulkheads (made of light wood and plastic material) to have been torn from their original positions. 
After switching on the lighter (and in a fraction of a second) the victim bent down and tried to protect his face with his arms, which caused him to have multiple burn damage on his upper members, torso and face. 

The facts that the kitchen is so exiguous and with an opened door that lead directly to the fish closed deck and also the inexistence of a dangerous atmosphere alarm device (fixed and/or portable) contributed to the event sequence: 
    1. The vessel arrived to the port, in order to be moored and the fishing nets were stored with fish residues (there was no washing nor cleaning of the nets); 
        2. The nets were stored in a closed compartment, without appropriate ventilation and possibly with an air temperature above 25°C, for more than 24 hours; 
        3. The crew (including the victim) arrived to the vessel two days later, unaware of any danger on board; 
        4. The fisherman/victim arrived to the kitchen and smelled the air which was with a stronger smell of ammonia-like than usual; 
        5. Even though in presence of a high volatile and inflammable substance, the victim switched on a lighter inside the kitchen area – Casualty event.

The contributive factors for the accident were (not intended to be by the order of the event sequence): 

1. Lack of training that led into a misinterpretation of the reality, facing the data obtained by the smell. It led the victim not to carry on safety procedures such as opening the portholes (in order to have a lower concentration of dangerous gas), the use of a mask or to close the door of the kitchen (it could be more effective if it would be closed on the day after the fishing labour); 
 2.  Besides the lack of training, the victim didn’t have any alarm device that could warn him about the presence of a dangerous atmosphere; 

3. For those conditions, the ship didn’t have forced or enough natural ventilation of this confined space; 

4. Possibly it was an high temperature inside the confined space (peak of summer); 

5. The concentration of the trimethylamine overcame its lower limit of explosion (2,0  Vol.-% (49 g/m3)); 

6. The nets were not enough cleaned or washed in order to ensure the safety of its storage on board the vessel “EÇA DE QUEIRÓS”, for more than 24 hours; 

7. There are no procedures on board to deal with this kind of danger. 

The above factors 3; 4; 5 and 6 are connected in a way that 3; 4 and 6 directly contributed to 5. The factor 3 could be a contribution to factor 4. Factors 7; 1; 3 and 6 are connected as well.

On 26 February 2013 at 0545(LT), Celebrity Century was anchored in Kailua Kona, Hawaii, commencing tender boat operations.  When tender boat/lifeboat no. 10 (tender boat no. 10) was extended, and before lowering it, the forward wire rope fall parted, causing the tender boat to swivel on the aft hook.  The tender boat remained hanging by the aft hook, which then ripped off its base, causing the boat to fall in the water, bow first, at an approximate angle of 45° and a height of 15 m. 

The tender boat remained afloat upright.  The fall caused damage to the tender boat’s hull and upper structure.  Subsequently, it was boarded by engineers and all fuel tanks were isolated.  No flooding occurred and no oil spills were reported.  A second ship’s tender boat was used to tow the damaged tender boat ashore.  As a precautionary measure, an oil boom was deployed around the damaged tender boat.  A third tender boat was used to retrieve the floating equipment and life jackets in the water that fell from tender boat no. 10.  At the time of the accident, no crew members were inside tender boat no. 10 and no injuries occurred. 

The safety investigation found that: 
the wire rope had parted at a site of severe pre-existing corrosion wastage, which reduced the wire rope’s cross-section and load carrying capacity; 
it required Scanning Electron Microscope (SEM) and Energy Dispersive X-ray Spectroscopy (EDS) analysis to determine that the wire rope’s crowns exhibited severe corrosion attack representing as much as 50% reduction in its cross-section.  Therefore, a change in the internal cross-section of the wire rope would not have been evident by visual examination such as that performed by either the ship’s crew or the contracted external technicians; 
the laboratory analysis of the grease from the failed wire rope revealed that it was contaminated with high concentrations of the elemental components of sea water as well as metals, including iron and zinc, thus precluding it from serving as an anti-corrosive protection; 
the extensive corrosion of the failed wire rope was due to lack of adequate anti-corrosive protection sometime during its life.  The corrosion could have either initiated shortly after manufacture due to lack of grease, or as a result of insufficient grease, premature loss of grease, and/or loss of grease protective properties during its service life; 
the Company had prepared processes for ordering, supplying, maintaining and inspecting the wire ropes; however, they were not integrated as an overall safety system to manage the long term integrity of the wire ropes.

On January, 24th, 2013, around 1400, ship “Karina G.” was alongside the commercial berth of Figueira da Foz by portside, unloading  eucalyptus trunk bales.  The victim was in the ship’s cargo hold, astern, assisting the unloading operations. After completing the setting of the load sling, he walked to a safety position, before the crane started to hoist the wood trunk bale in order to put it outboard the ship, he missed stepping with one foot. He struck on one of the wood trunks and felt into a lower position between a wood bale and the portside bulwark.  This casualty is considered a serious one, notwithstanding the fact that it had resulted to the extended immobilization of the injured person caused by the high fall, it had provoked the extended immobilization of the injured person. The conclusions of the investigation had been:
a) The worker wearied the PPE recommended and provided by his employer by march 2012 (working suit, foot-wear, helmet, gloves);The victim was not subjected to an occupation that implied an excessive fatigue state;
b)  The surface over where the onboard stevedores had to move, was specially irregular and slippery. The risk would be increased by the fact that it had a vegetal nature and was wet;
c) Despite of the fact of the outer sole of the working boot was a non-slippery one, it was not specially adapted to an irregular surface with a high risk of slippery.
d) By not having a OSH service in the company, the internal weighting of the risks posed by different ships types of cargo operating and environmental conditions is not performed in a systematic, continuous and objective way, but is rather considered generically.
